Mafdet is the primary western coastal terminus for eastern desert artifact trade; goods from pyramids and oases reach Mafdet's Ledger Houses for export documentation and maritime transport.
The Strandline Compact's dual-attestation protocol was designed partly to prevent single-authority record manipulation like the Sultan's Palace's Corrective Harmonization — the explicit negative example in Ledger House institutional history.
Mafdet's dual-provenance classification — oasis-provenance, pyramid-provenance, and dual-origin objects — provides the most detailed commercial taxonomy for eastern desert materials in current practice.
Cargo origin attestation requires traceable documentation through at least one oasis authentication point; artifacts without it are classified as eastern desert corridor uncertain, reducing commercial value by a standard margin.
Mafdet's maritime insurance rates for corridor artifact cargo are calibrated against the three oasis flow reports as primary data sources.

