Kethari geological memory encompasses the full Deepwell Confluence aquifer system: primary vent at the Great Oasis, secondary fracture at the Southern Oasis, tertiary fracture at the Northern Oasis, and the Iseth Reach canal connections to all three pyramid sites.
The memory includes the Iseth Reach's drying as a multi-generational process; practitioners can confirm engineers at pyramid sites had time to observe the decline and partially prepare.
Kethari route memory preserves historical waystation locations and spring viability assessments predating all existing charter stone records — a resource expedition planners have consulted to recover lost route information.
The Ninth Meridian Rite's failure is preserved in deep-stone memory as a seismic event sequence distinguishable from natural earthquake activity by timing, pattern, and epicenter distribution.
Aquifer connections between the oases and pyramid sites remain intact as geological formations; a new engineering effort could restore them using existing geological pathways.

