Khephari geological assessment identifies three distinct formation types: primary vent sandstone at the Great Oasis, tertiary fracture limestone at the Northern Oasis, and volcanic-adjacent rock at the Southern Pyramid site.
The charter road alignment follows geological ridge lines visible in surface topography: the Keepers chose routes with stable subgrade, reduced windward exposure, and access to subsurface water at waystation intervals.
The Iseth Reach's vanished drainage channel is recoverable in surface geology: the former riverbed is visible as a slightly depressed alluvial corridor filled with finer-grained sediment than surrounding desert pavement.
The Great Pyramid sits on the most stable geological foundation — primary basement rock rather than sandstone or volcanic formations — correlating with its greater institutional and physical durability.
Khephari assessment: major corridor hazards are hydrological, not geological. The aquifer system remains intact but engineered access points are degraded; geological conditions support infrastructure restoration if institutional sponsorship were available.
